There will be a JV Football scrimmage tomorrow at 12:00 vs Knott Co @ home.
If you plan on coming to a football game this season, please follow the guidelines below.
We have to adhere to the guidelines for our athletes to be able to continue their season.
Even though it is outside, face masks ARE required at all times for fans, and social distancing.

Come out and support our kids if you can, and show them Cavaliers can safely and proudly return to sports! #GOCAVS

post_text: Staying healthy is an important part of education. If your child doesn’t have health insurance, you may qualify for KCHIP, Kentucky Children’s Health Insurance Program. It provides comprehensive coverage at no cost. There are many students across the district who qualify but are not signed up. To find out more, go to kidshealth.ky.gov or call (877) 524-4718 – because every child needs health insurance.

post_text: Also accepting a new role this year is Mr. Brian Bentley. Mr. Bentley is a graduate of Morehead State University, where he got his teaching degree and Masters in Middle School Education. He attained his Rank I certification from the University of the Cumberlands. He is married to Lisa Lucas Bentley, a graduate of Jenkins High School. They have one son, Jacob Bentley, who just graduated from Jenkins in 2020 and who is currently attending Morehead State University. Brian has taught for 27 years plus one year of substitute teaching. He served as School Technology Coordinator for all of those 27 years. This year he has accepted a position at the district level in the role of Instructional Supervisor and Digital Learning Coach. He hopes to apply what he has learned to help the teachers make this unprecedented year an awesome one for all the students of Jenkins Independent School.

He served as School Technology Coordinator for all of those 27 years. This year he has accepted a position at the district level in the role of Instructional Supervisor and Digital Learning Coach. He hopes to apply what he has learned to help the teachers make this unprecedented year an awesome one for all the students of Jenkins Independent School.

post_text: In addition to our new teachers, we have some staff that have been promoted to new positions. Mr. Doug Barnett is the new Director of Technology for Jenkins Independent. Mr. Barnett is a graduate of Pikeville College, where he graduated with a bachelor's in Middle School Education with an emphasis on Mathematics and Social Studies. He earned his master's degree and Rank 1 from Morehead State University, holding a certification in Instructional Leadership Supervisor of Instruction. Mr. Barnett has extensive experience and certifications in educational technology, having worked in the field in Perry County schools, Hazard Independent, and Jenkins Independent. He has two children and two grandchildren. Mr. Barnett says that his primary goal is to meet the needs of the students and staff at Jenkins to the best of his ability.

post_text: Jenkins Schools would like to welcome Mr. Jeremy Bell as a Special Education teacher. Mr. Bell has attended Georgetown College, the University of Pikeville, and Morehead State University. He is married to Melissa, who will be working at Jenkins as a speech language pathologist. The Bells have three children: Evan, who is 13, and twin daughters Kourtlyn and Kennedy, age 10. Mr. Bell has most recently worked in the petroleum industry and has been heavily involved in youth sports. In addition to his teaching duties, he will also be the high school baseball coach and high school football defensive coordinator. Mr. Bell is happy to have the unique opportunity to make a difference in the lives of children and to be a positive influence for them, not only in the classroom, but also on the ball field.

post_text: Jenkins Independent would like to introduce our community to our new middle school Social Studies teacher, Ms. Jenna Robinson. Ms. Robinson recently graduated from the University of Pikeville with a bachelor's degree in History & Political Science. She is currently enrolled at the University of the Cumberlands in the Masters of Arts in Teaching program. Ms. Robinson comes from a loving family that supports her in everything she does. She has been dating her high school sweetheart for the past seven years and has a dog named Truman, after President Harry S. Truman. She is excited to begin her teaching career at Jenkins, where she will be able to work one on one with her students and get to know and understand them better. She can't wait to meet her students and teach them all about Social Studies. Welcome, Ms. Robinson!

post_text:
Jenkins Independent Schools are excited to announce the hiring of Duane Noble as our high school football coach. Coach Noble was a 1988 Fleming-Neon High School graduate where he excelled in football. Noble played football for Union college. He has coached at all levels from peewee through high school in various capacities.
Noble spent many years as a social worker and currently teaches for Eastern Kentucky University and the University of Louisville. Coach Noble has a passion for the game of football and for teaching. His goal for Jenkins football is not just to win games, but to teach work ethic and responsibility while molding his players into young men.
Jenkins is happy to welcome Coach Noble to the Cavalier family!

post_text: Jenkins Elementary School will have a "Drive-Thru Celebration" for their students on Friday, June 5th. Students will have the opportunity to pick up report cards, materials left behind in the classroom, pictures, certificates, etc and drop off any remaining school items such as reading books or library books. Rules: Stay inside of your car at all times, follow the same traffic pattern as drop-off/pickup, smile and say your final goodbye to the 2019/2020 school year. Schedule: 5th grade at 10:00, 4th grade at 10:30, 3rd grade at 11:00, 2nd grade at 11:30, 1st grade at 12:00, kindergarten at 12:30 and Pre-K at 12:30. We look forward to seeing you there!

post_text:
Zion Family Ministries in Wise will be hosting “Project Prom” this Saturday, March 7, 2020 from 1-5pm.
Zion Family Ministries is located behind Marshall’s.
Ladies, along with a dress (they have sizes 0-22), you will receive shoes, jewelry, flowers, and lots of other extras.
Refreshments will be provided as well as a boutique type atmosphere to make everyone feel comfortable.
This is open to all schools and if you need transportation, let them know and they will provide transportation for you.

post_text: This week at Jenkins Elementary
text: This week at Jenkins Elementary

post_text:
Jenkins Elementary

Cavalier Families!
Come join us for breakfast and enjoy fresh baked goods from the Cavalier Cafeteria to celebrate Dr Seuss Week/Read Across America and National School Breakfast Week! Each student will be allotted two free adult passes, the cost for each additional person is $2.00. Families will be allowed to shop at Book Fair after breakfast! Class schedules are as follows:
Wednesday: Kindergarten and 1st Grade
Thursday: Pre-K and 2nd Grade
Friday: 3rd Grade, 4th Grade, and 5th Grade
Breakfast will begin at 9:00, if you have any questions, please feel free to call the office!

post_text:
ALL JMHS SENIORS and Guardians of Seniors:
The KY Work Ready scholarship is here to help your student pay for a certificate or degree in a local in-demand field! Click the following link for more info, https://www.kheaa.com/website/kheaa/work_ready?main=1, or contact your GEAR UP staff at your school to complete the application! The KY Work Ready Scholarship could pay for the full cost of tuition for completing an associate’s degree. You don’t need to have a certain GPA or be low-income to apply! This is about supporting students in getting degrees in high-demand jobs in KY.
